body:
Hi,

Please look at this issue:
https://github.com/flutter/flutter/issues/103397

I have a problem with my debugger. If I create a new project, I can use the debugger like normal.
But in my daily work project, the debugger just runs over all breakpoints. They turn from red breakpoints into grey stop signs. What can I do to find out the problem and solve it?

comment_data.body:
This is tough to debug without being able to reproduce. I believe if the breakpoints are turning grey, that means our file mapping didn't work in the VM service; however, it looks like there are cases where the breakpoints remain red but still don't get triggered. The implementation of file mapping in web is different from mobile, but it sounds like this project isn't set up to do mobile so we can't check whether this is web-specific. 

Can you send your IntelliJ logs? Help > Show logs in finder, then send us idea.log. This will contain file names of your project, so let me know if you'd prefer me to send you an email for them.
same issue. debug point doesn't stop anymore with flutter 3.0

@bhanuka96 are you also in flutter web? I'm not able to reproduce in my small project for flutter 3.0+. If you can send me IntelliJ logs (instructions above: https://github.com/flutter/flutter-intellij/issues/6159#issuecomment-1125539843) that could help.
I'm not sure gradle would have an impact on debug breakpoints. Logs would be the most helpful for trying to narrow down where the problem is coming from.

@helin24 @stevemessick 
I did pup get. It does not change everything.
pup upgrade too.
I deleted .idea .dart_lang and the build folder. It is still not working.

[mymonitor.zip](https://github.com/flutter/flutter-intellij/files/8714056/mymonitor.zip)
Try yourself. I deleted my code from the project. Try to set a breakpoint at the print in the main. In my case it just runs over it.

I'm also experiencing the same issue. 

Have tried:
Switching to master -> didn't help
Reinstalling dart & Flutter plugins -> didn't help
Reinstalled the SDK -> also didn't work for me

Running on Android real device (Samsung Note 9)

@SilentThunder89 @Dkrinker I'm not able to reproduce this myself on mac with the versions you mentioned, so can you send me your IntelliJ logs? Help > Show logs in finder, then send us idea.log. This will contain file names of your project, so let me know if you'd prefer me to send you an email for them.

> @SilentThunder89 @Dkrinker I'm not able to reproduce this myself on mac with the versions you mentioned, so can you send me your IntelliJ logs? Help > Show logs in finder, then send us idea.log. This will contain file names of your project, so let me know if you'd prefer me to send you an email for them.

Can you please send me your email?

@Dkrinker My email is helinx@google.com

Can you also let me know the Dart version you're using for your project? This can be found in Preferences> Languages & Frameworks > Dart.

For anyone on macos - I suspect the issue is coming from having a space somewhere in the path of your project. Just now I tried making a hello flutter project in `~/Documents/tests/with space/hello_flutter_space` and I got the same failure as @Dkrinker (thanks for the logs!). I'll work on a solution for this, but for now you can try moving your project to a directory without spaces if that's convenient.

For the windows issue, there's an error thrown by the VM service, and I'm not sure what's causing that. I have a project that reproduces the problem and I'll look into this further. If you're blocked on this, unfortunately I think the best suggestion I have now is to drop back to the previous version of the plugin.

> For anyone on macos - I suspect the issue is coming from having a space somewhere in the path of your project. Just now I tried making a hello flutter project in `~/Documents/tests/with space/hello_flutter_space` and I got the same failure as @Dkrinker (thanks for the logs!). I'll work on a solution for this, but for now you can try moving your project to a directory without spaces if that's convenient.

That worked for me!  Thank you

The difference between this project and hello_world is the base change in the index.html. Works on my mac but not on windows - investigating...


As a workaround, the users can temporary revert the base change in `index.html` to ` <base href="$FLUTTER_BASE_HREF">`.

I had the same issue on linux with latest flutter/dart/plugins (for desktop dev).

It looks like the issue is also related to the path. If I open a project through a symlink it does not work. If I open it through the resolved path it works. It looks like the path is resolved at execution and the IDE is not able to match the unresolved and the resolved paths.

Edit: I've made a separate issue for this: #6196
@mullerch could you please open a separate issue for this so we can properly track the fix?

@mullerch I ran into this issue while using Linux and chrome: https://github.com/flutter/flutter-intellij/issues/6193

But it sounds like you have a different problem, as my issue occurred regardless of whether the project involved a symlink. Could you open a separate issue and describe further (or include screenshots) what you mean by "the path is resolved at execution and the IDE is not able to match the unresolved and the resolved paths"?
It looks to me that the issues reported here have been fixed. Please let us know if that is not the case.
